revision.text:
[[ja:庚申待]]
'''Kōshin‑machi'''（庚申待, こうしんまち） is a folk‑religious observance in {{ill|Japan|ja|日本}} in which deities and buddhas are venerated and an all‑night vigil is kept on a {{ill|Kōshin|ja|庚申}} day. It is also called {{ill|Yoikōshin|ja|宵庚申}} and {{ill|Osaru‑machi|ja|おさる待ち}}. Kōshin‑machi is usually conducted collectively at the village level; the gathering ({{ill|kō (confraternity)|ja|講}}) is called a '''{{ill|Kōshin‑kō|ja|庚申講}}'''（こうしんこう）, '''{{ill|Kōshin‑e|ja|庚申会}}'''（こうしんえ）, or {{ill|Ohi‑machi|ja|お日待ち}}.

== Overview ==
Kōshin‑machi is based on legends from {{ill|Taoism|ja|道教}}, a folk religion of {{ill|China|ja|中国}}. It was believed that three worms called the {{ill|Three Corpses|ja|三尸}} (彭侯子・彭常子・命児子) dwell in a person’s head, abdomen, and legs and constantly watch that person’s misdeeds. On the night of a Kōshin day, while the person is asleep, the Three Corpses ascend to heaven and report the person’s conduct to the heavenly sovereign (also called “{{ill|Yama (Buddhism)|ja|閻魔大王}}”); depending on the offenses, one’s lifespan might be shortened or, after death, one might fall into the {{ill|Three evil paths|ja|三悪趣}} of hell, hungry ghosts, and animals. Therefore, to prevent the Three Corpses from ascending to heaven, villagers would gather to venerate the deities and then stay awake—often drinking together—until dawn. This is Kōshin‑machi.<ref>{{ill|Nishikado Masayoshi|ja|西角井正慶}} (ed.), 『{{ill|Encyclopedia of Annual Events|ja|年中行事事典}}』, {{ill|Tōkyōdō Shuppan|ja|東京堂出版}}, first ed. 23 May 1958, p.297.</ref> Monuments called {{ill|Kōshin‑tō|ja|庚申塔}}, erected to commemorate having continued Kōshin‑machi for three years (eighteen observances), still remain in many places.

It is thought to have been transmitted to Japan long ago; a story about Kōshin‑machi appears in {{ill|The Pillow Book|ja|枕草子}}. It spread among commoners after the start of the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}. Although {{ill|Kōshin faith|ja|庚申信仰}} has now declined, in some regions the observance continues under names such as fellowship or social gatherings.

In {{ill|Buddhism|ja|仏教}}, the principal deities for Kōshin are {{ill|Shōmen Kongō|ja|青面金剛}} and {{ill|Indra|ja|帝釈天}}; in {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道}} it is {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|猿田彦神}}. This is thought to derive from linking the character “申” in Kōshin with the {{ill|Japanese macaque|ja|サル}} (saru) of Sarutahiko. Monkeys are regarded as messengers of Kōshin, and {{ill|Kōshin‑tō|ja|庚申塔}} often bear carvings of the {{ill|Three wise monkeys|ja|三猿}} (“see no evil, speak no evil, hear no evil”). {{ill|Sannō Shintō|ja|山王信仰}} (the “three‑monkeys” cult) is also said to have arisen from this.

== See also ==
* {{ill|Kōshin faith|ja|庚申信仰}}
* {{ill|Sexagenary cycle|ja|干支}}
* {{ill|Kōshin Kaidō|ja|庚申街道}}
* {{ill|Kōshin‑dō|ja|庚申堂}}
* {{ill|Kōshin‑ji|ja|庚申寺}}
* {{ill|Ten Kings faith|ja|十王信仰}}
* {{ill|Sarubobo|ja|さるぼぼ}}
* {{ill|Kōshin‑sha|ja|庚申社}}

